Describe 3 latest advances in Big Bang cosmology

Here are three of the most significant **recent advances** in Big Bang cosmology—based on developments up to February 25, 2026—each reshaping our understanding of the early universe:

---

**1. The Earliest Supernova Detected (GRB 250314A at z ≈ 7.3)**  
In December 2025, astronomers confirmed the detection of the earliest-known supernova, associated with the gamma-ray burst GRB 250314A, occurring roughly 730 million years after the Big Bang (redshift ~7.3). Detected on March 14, 2025, by the SVOM satellite and followed up by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST), this event offers a rare glimpse into massive star formation and explosion mechanisms during the Epoch of Reionization ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GRB_250314A?utm_source=openai)).

This landmark observation challenges prior models by demonstrating that such collapsar-driven supernovae—massive stars collapsing into black holes—were already occurring much earlier than previously confirmed, providing key data about early cosmic chemical enrichment and black hole seeding ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GRB_250314A?utm_source=openai)).

---

**2. Discovery of Dusty, Metal-Rich Galaxies Just 500 Million Years Post-Big Bang**  
Just days ago, studies using JWST and the Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array (ALMA) identified approximately 70 faint, dusty galaxies in existence less than 1 billion years after the Big Bang—some dating back to just 500 million years post-Big Bang. Remarkably, these galaxies exhibit unexpectedly high abundances of heavy elements (“metals”), indicating rapid chemical evolution in the universe’s infancy ([space.com](https://www.space.com/astronomy/james-webb-space-telescope/these-70-dusty-galaxies-at-the-edge-of-our-universe-could-rewrite-our-understanding-of-the-cosmos?utm_source=openai)).

These findings upend established models of galaxy formation, which assumed such metal enrichment and dust accumulation occurred much later. Moreover, they suggest a progressive evolutionary link between ultrabright star-forming galaxies, quiescent galactic systems, and these newly found dusty galaxies ([space.com](https://www.space.com/astronomy/james-webb-space-telescope/these-70-dusty-galaxies-at-the-edge-of-our-universe-could-rewrite-our-understanding-of-the-cosmos?utm_source=openai)).

---

**3. Recreation of the Quark-Gluon Plasma’s Liquid-like Behavior at the LHC**  
Physicists at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) recently recreated conditions from the universe’s first millisecond, studying the quark-gluon plasma (QGP)—a primordial state of matter. Their observations reveal that this plasma behaves as an ultrahot fluid rather than a simple gas. The team detected a subtle “wake,” or dip in particle density (under a 1% change), caused by quarks plowing through the plasma. They tracked the effect using Z bosons, which serve as neutral tracers, marking the first clear observation of a quark-induced wake ([livescience.com](https://www.livescience.com/physics-mathematics/particle-physics/physicists-recreated-the-first-millisecond-after-the-big-bang-and-found-it-was-surprisingly-soupy?utm_source=openai)).

This breakthrough provides direct insight into the dynamics of the early universe’s initial microsecond, refining our understanding of how the QGP behaved and evolved.

---

Together, these three advances offer breakthroughs across different cosmic epochs:

- The **GRB 250314A supernova** informs us about massive star deaths and black hole births during the Epoch of Reionization.
- The **dusty, metal-rich galaxies** expose rapid chemical evolution and challenge existing models of galaxy formation during cosmic dawn.
- The **LHC’s quark-gluon plasma findings** illuminate the fundamental physics governing the universe’s earliest instants.

Each development not only adds a critical piece to the cosmic puzzle but also underscores how observational capabilities—from JWST to particle accelerators—are enabling us to peel back layers of the universe’s earliest chapters.
